evidence: Although replacing Ta with Ti results in a reduction of compressive yield strength from 1762 to 1243 MPa, the fracture strain is greatly enhanced from 7.3 to 44.3%, indicating that the strength-ductility balance can be tuned to a large extent in this RHEA system.

The ST-1300/24 alloys exhibit good compressive ductility without fracture during loading. Their yield strength σ 0.2 is reduced from 1304, 1112, to 973 MPa with the substitution of Ta with Ti. After aging at 600 °C for 24 h, the yield strength is enhanced up to 1762, 1509, and 1243 MPa of the Ta 25 Ti 25 , Ta 20 Ti 30 , and Ta 15 Ti 35 alloys, respectively. As mentioned above, although high strengths are commonly seen in the RHEAs containing basket-weave-like BCC/B2 microstructures, most previous alloys exhibited very low compressive ductility (< 10%)  [21, 44] . Here, in contrast, the forming for B2 and Omega phases reduces the yield strength but greatly enhances the ductility ε, from 7.3% for Ta 25 Ti 25 , 21.6% for Ta 20 Ti 30 to 44.3% for Ta 15 Ti 35 alloy.
The Ta 25 Ti 25 alloy exhibits the highest strength of 1762 MPa but very limited ductility below 10%
